\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard
Human activity recognition using deep electroencephalography learning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
introduces a deep learning-based framework for classifying EEG artifacts
 (FCEA)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
involving a Convolutional Neural Network and a Long Short-Term Memory Recurrent
 Neural Network.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
a 3-class dataset of EEG activities was created.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ameras, accelerometers, gyroscopes and sound sensors have been used to detect
 the movement of users in automatic Human Activity Recognition (HAR) systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In HAR system design, Machine Learning (ML) algorithms have made signiﬁcant
 progress in the extraction of human activity fea- tures from sensor data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
7% of the studies used only a combination of CNNs and RNNs, whereas, 40
 % used only CNNs and 14 % used only RNNs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
whilst reading printed text, speaking out loudly and watching a TV program.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The technologies used for detecting human actions are commonly based on
 heterogeneous sensors placed throughout the environment, such as cameras
 and wearable sensors equipped with accelerometers, gyroscopes and biosensors
 [1–4].
 Cameras provide video data in form of a 3D matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The CNNs are more appropriate for learning and interpreting camera and motion-de
tection sensor data.
 The LSTM networks are not capable of classifying video data alone.
 They, however, attain a desirable classiﬁcation performance when they are
 used for modeling accelerometer and gyroscope raw data, as well as the
 feature maps populated by a CNN [2].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, the smartphone and smartwatches which have been mostly used in
 HAR, are not suitable for recognizing facial activities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Analyzing and training a neural network on EGG (Electroencephalography)
 data involves several steps.
 Here's a general guide to get you started:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 **Understand the EGG Data:** - Familiarize yourself with the structure
 and characteristics of the EEG data you have.
 Understand the number of channels, sampling frequency, and the duration
 of the recordings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 **Preprocess the Data:** - Clean the data by removing artifacts and noise.
 Common preprocessing steps include filtering, artifact removal, and normalizati
on.
 - Segment the data into epochs.
 This involves dividing the continuous EEG signal into smaller, manageable
 chunks, often aligned with specific events or stimuli.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 **Feature Extraction:** - Extract relevant features from the EEG epochs.
 Common features include power spectral density, time-domain features, and
 statistical measures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4.
 **Data Splitting:** - Split your data into training, validation, and test
 sets.
 This is crucial for evaluating your model's performance on unseen data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
5.
 **Build a Neural Network Model:** - Choose or design a neural network architect
ure suitable for your task.
 For time-series data like EEG, recurrent neural networks (RNNs) or long
 short-term memory networks (LSTMs) are often used.
 Alternatively, you can use 1D convolutional neural networks (CNNs).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
6.
 **Model Training:** - Train your neural network on the training dataset.
 Use the validation set to monitor the model's performance and prevent overfitti
ng.
 - Experiment with different hyperparameters, architectures, and regularization
 techniques to improve performance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
7.
 **Evaluation:** - Evaluate your trained model on the test set to assess
 its generalization to new, unseen data.
 - Use appropriate metrics for your task, such as accuracy, precision, recall,
 or specific metrics relevant to EEG analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
8.
 **Interpretation:** - Interpret the results and gain insights into the
 neural network's performance.
 Understand which features contribute most to the model's predictions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
9.
 **Fine-Tuning and Optimization:** - If necessary, fine-tune your model
 or explore advanced techniques to improve performance, such as transfer
 learning or ensemble methods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
10.
 **Documentation and Reporting:** - Document your approach, findings, and
 any challenges faced during the analysis.
 This is crucial for reproducibility and collaboration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remember that the specific steps and techniques may vary based on the nature
 of your EEG data and the task you are trying to solve.
 Always adapt your approach based on the characteristics of your data and
 the goals of your analysis.
\end_layout

